+# Receptionist Task - beyond-de-giorgi step-014
+
+Question:
+
+Identify the smallest repository-local source set that can support Chain Step 2
+for the active beyond-de-giorgi branch
+`Quantified Reformulation Audit With Anti-Repackaging, Early Endpoint Exchange,
+And Interface-Aware Budgeting`.
+
+I need exact file recommendations for all of the following:
+
+1. the bounded candidate slate:
+   at most two active exact reformulation families and one reserve, chosen from
+   repository-native exact reformulation families already on record;
+2. the exact full equations for each likely active candidate, including the
+   exact unknown/package and the precise nonlinear structure rather than only
+   packaging language;
+3. the localized equations that actually touch the frozen LEI burden
+   `I_flux[phi] = ∬ (|u|^2 + 2p) u · ∇phi`,
+   together with immediate debt entries:
+   cutoff commutators,
+   pressure re-entry,
+   vector reconstruction,
+   admissibility,
+   and locality loss;
+4. the endpoint-exchange path, if any, from each candidate's native-variable
+   language back to the same frozen LEI burden currency;
+5. the nearest prior-art comparator on the repository record for each likely
+   active candidate, plus the sharpest local file on whether the claimed delta
+   already looks absorbed; and
+6. the strongest repository-local evidence for an early Step-2 kill condition,
+   if the exchange path or prior-art delta is already visibly absent.
+
+Constraints:
+
+- Use only files inside this repository.
+- Prefer existing factual and meta-library files, prior beyond-de-giorgi
+  library-inbox reports, and run-009 planning artifacts.
+- Keep the candidate list bounded to two active families and one reserve.
+- Do not run the formal Step-3 anti-repackaging classification.
+- If the exact-rewrite record is already narrow enough to force a Step-2
+  negative verdict, say so explicitly and point to the exact files.
+- Distinguish exact rewrite families from older pressure-branch or geometry
+  materials when recommending sources.
